{"title_page": "Dick Dreux", "text_new": "{{Orphan|date=April 2020}}\n\n'''Dirk Johannes Hendrik (Dick) Dreux''' (27 May 1913 \u2013 1978) was a Dutch writer of historical literature.\n\n==Biography==\nDick Dreux was born in Amsterdam as a child of Hendrik Johannes Wilhelm Dreux and Cornelia Hendrika Johanna Lucke who divorced in 1921. He grew up with his grandparents from his mother's side. He attended the [[Hogere Burger School]] and in 1929, at age 16, joined the merchant navy. His adventurous life led him around the world and finally to Spain, where he fought against Franco's fascists in the [[Spanish Civil War]]. He returned to the Netherlands just before the start of [[World War II]] in order to fulfill his military duty and keep his Dutch citizenship. He was interned in [[Amersfoort concentration camp]], and then labored in a work camp on the German island of [[Borkum]].<ref name=vondel>{{cite web|url=http://www.bertvanvondel.nl/dick-dreux-1913-78-kritisch-auteur/|accessdate=20 February 2019|language=nl|title=Dick Dreux, 1913-\u201978, kritisch auteur|date=29 October 2017|first=Bert|last=van Vondel}}</ref>\n\nAfter the end of the war, he became an author, writing historical literature from a critical point of view, many of it published by the [[Arbeiderspers]], then a socialist publishing house. Dreux and his wife lived in Amsterdam, and later moved to a houseboat in [[Bussum]]. He free-lanced for magazines and newspapers and then worked for [[Omroepvereniging VARA|VARA]], writing over 450 [[radio play]]s between 1959 and 1970. He also wrote [[Serial (literature)|serial stories]] for children's magazines like ''[[Donald Duck (Dutch comic book)|Donald Duck]]'' starting in the 1950s, and a number of his stories were illustrated by [[Hans Kresse]] and published as comic books. His style was accessible and conversational, for which he credited his grandfather, a \"born storyteller\".<ref name=vondel/>\n\nDreux died on 6 December 1978 in hospital in Naarden, and was buried in Bussum.<ref name=vondel/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dreux, Dick}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Dutch male writers]]\n[[Category:Amersfoort concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:People from Bussum]]\n[[Category:Writers from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch people of the Spanish Civil War]]\n", "text_old": "'''Dirk Johannes Hendrik (Dick) Dreux''' (27 May 1913-1978) was a Dutch writer of historical literature.\n\n==Biography==\nDick Dreux was born in Amsterdam as a child of Hendrik Johannes Wilhelm Dreux and Cornelia Hendrika Johanna Lucke who divorced in 1921. He grew up with his grandparents from his mother's side. He attended the [[Hogere Burger School]] and in 1929, at age 16, joined the merchant navy. His adventurous life led him around the world and finally to Spain, where he fought against Franco's fascists in the [[Spanish Civil War]]. He returned to the Netherlands just before the start of [[World War II]] in order to fulfill his military duty and keep his Dutch citizenship. He was interned in [[Amersfoort concentration camp]], and then labored in a work camp on the German island of [[Borkum]].<ref name=vondel>{{cite web|url=http://www.bertvanvondel.nl/dick-dreux-1913-78-kritisch-auteur/|accessdate=20 February 2019|language=nl|title=Dick Dreux, 1913-\u201978, kritisch auteur|date=29 October 2017|first=Bert|last=van Vondel}}</ref>\n\nAfter the end of the war, he became an author, writing historical literature from a critical point of view, many of it published by the [[Arbeiderspers]], then a socialist publishing house. Dreux and his wife lived in Amsterdam, and later moved to a houseboat in [[Bussum]]. He free-lanced for magazines and newspapers and then worked for [[Omroepvereniging VARA|VARA]], writing over 450 [[radio play]]s between 1959 and 1970. He also wrote [[Serial (literature)|serial stories]] for children's magazines like ''[[Donald Duck (Dutch comic book)|Donald Duck]]'' starting in the 1950s, and a number of his stories were illustrated by [[Hans Kresse]] and published as comic books. His style was accessible and conversational, for which he credited his grandfather, a \"born storyteller\".<ref name=vondel/>\n\nDreux died on 6 December 1978 in hospital in Naarden, and was buried in Bussum.<ref name=vondel/>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Dreux, Dick}}\n[[Category:1913 births]]\n[[Category:1978 deaths]]\n[[Category:20th-century Dutch male writers]]\n[[Category:Amersfoort concentration camp survivors]]\n[[Category:People from Bussum]]\n[[Category:Writers from Amsterdam]]\n[[Category:Dutch people of the Spanish Civil War]]\n", "name_user": "Ser Amantio di Nicolao", "label": "safe", "comment": "add authority control, addedorphantag", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Dick_Dreux"}
